00:01:02.420 --> 00:01:04.440
Situation number one.

00:01:04.660 --> 00:01:07.380
Someone asks you a question

00:01:07.380 --> 00:01:09.540
but you don't know the answer.

00:01:09.640 --> 00:01:12.660
Excuse me, do you know if the Bluetooth adapter

00:01:12.660 --> 00:01:15.400
will work on the Sony A6400?

00:01:15.760 --> 00:01:17.800
Ahhh... I don't know.

00:01:19.140 --> 00:01:21.400
When someone asks you a question

00:01:21.400 --> 00:01:24.220
and you simply don't know the answer,

00:01:24.360 --> 00:01:27.620
well never say "I don't know".

00:01:27.620 --> 00:01:29.620
Even though this is the truth,

00:01:29.920 --> 00:01:34.480
even though, those are the correct English words to say,

00:01:34.560 --> 00:01:36.960
you're not being helpful at all!

00:01:36.960 --> 00:01:40.160
So, saying "I don't know" in the workplace -

00:01:40.160 --> 00:01:41.600
especially to a customer -

00:01:41.600 --> 00:01:44.900
sounds really unprofessional in English,

00:01:44.900 --> 00:01:47.240
even a little bit rude.

00:01:47.240 --> 00:01:49.120
It's like saying you don't care.

00:01:49.120 --> 00:01:51.020
So to sound more professional

00:01:51.020 --> 00:01:54.380
and to show that you do care, try saying

00:01:55.140 --> 00:01:58.140
"I'm not sure, but I can find out".

00:01:58.440 --> 00:01:59.900
So, say it with me,

00:02:06.320 --> 00:02:10.420
Or you could say "I'll find out for you."

00:02:12.520 --> 00:02:13.640
Awesome!

00:02:13.880 --> 00:02:15.100
Here's another one:

00:02:15.100 --> 00:02:17.100
"Let me come back to you on that"

00:02:17.640 --> 00:02:19.820
So, you can use this to say

00:02:19.820 --> 00:02:23.100
that you need a little more time to find the answer

00:02:23.100 --> 00:02:25.340
but you're assuring the person

00:02:25.340 --> 00:02:27.660
that you will try to help them.

00:02:31.200 --> 00:02:34.380
Excellent! You're sounding really helpful

